# Component Patterns

## Functional Components with Types

Always define and export prop types:

```tsx
export type ComponentNameProps = {
  requiredProp: string;
  optionalProp?: boolean;
  onAction?: () => void;
};

export const ComponentName = ({ requiredProp, optionalProp = false, onAction }: ComponentNameProps) => {
  // Component implementation
};
```

## UI Components

Use shadcn/ui components from `@sb/webapp-core/components/ui/`:

```tsx
import { Button } from '@sb/webapp-core/components/ui/button';
import { Card, CardContent, CardHeader, CardTitle } from '@sb/webapp-core/components/ui/card';
import { Dialog, DialogContent, DialogTrigger } from '@sb/webapp-core/components/ui/dialog';
import { Tooltip, TooltipContent, TooltipTrigger } from '@sb/webapp-core/components/ui/tooltip';
import { Avatar, AvatarImage, AvatarFallback } from '@sb/webapp-core/components/ui/avatar';
```

## Tooltip Pattern for Collapsed States

Wrap interactive elements with tooltips when in collapsed state:

```tsx
{isCollapsed ? (
  <Tooltip delayDuration={200}>
    <TooltipTrigger asChild>{content}</TooltipTrigger>
    <TooltipContent side="right">{label}</TooltipContent>
  </Tooltip>
) : (
  content
)}
```

## Context Usage

Use React Context for shared state:

```tsx
import { useContext } from 'react';
import { LayoutContext } from '../layout.context';

const { isSidebarCollapsed, toggleSidebar } = useContext(LayoutContext);
```

## Responsive Behavior

Use the `useMediaQuery` hook:

```tsx
import { useMediaQuery } from '@sb/webapp-core/hooks';
import { media } from '@sb/webapp-core/theme';

const { matches: isDesktop } = useMediaQuery({
  above: media.Breakpoint.TABLET,
});

// Combine with collapsed state
const isCollapsedDesktop = isSidebarCollapsed && isDesktop;
```

## Inline Action Buttons

For small inline action buttons (like resend, refresh, retry):

```tsx
import { RefreshCw } from 'lucide-react';

<Button
  variant="outline"
  size="sm"
  className="h-6 px-2 text-xs"
  onClick={handleAction}
  disabled={loading}
>
  <RefreshCw className={`h-3 w-3 mr-1 ${loading ? 'animate-spin' : ''}`} />
  <FormattedMessage id="Feature / Action" defaultMessage="Resend" />
</Button>
```

Key points:
- Use `variant="outline"` for visibility with border
- Use `size="sm"` with custom `className="h-6 px-2 text-xs"` for compact size
- Add spinning animation on loading: `${loading ? 'animate-spin' : ''}`
- Disable button during loading: `disabled={loading}`

## Conditional Rendering with Actions

Show different UI based on state with optional actions:

```tsx
{condition ? (
  <div className="flex items-center">
    <CheckIcon className="mr-2 w-4 h-4" />
    <FormattedMessage id="Feature / Yes" defaultMessage="Yes" />
  </div>
) : (
  <div className="flex items-center gap-2">
    <PendingIcon className="mr-2 w-4 h-4" />
    <FormattedMessage id="Feature / No" defaultMessage="No" />
    <ActionButton onClick={handleAction} loading={loading} />
  </div>
)}
```

## Multiple Mutations in One Component

When a component needs multiple mutations:

```tsx
const [commitUpdateMutation, { loading: updateLoading }] = useMutation(updateMutation, {
  onCompleted: () => toast({ description: updateSuccessMessage, variant: 'success' }),
  onError: () => toast({ description: updateFailMessage, variant: 'destructive' }),
});

const [commitDeleteMutation] = useMutation(deleteMutation, {
  onCompleted: () => {
    toast({ description: deleteSuccessMessage, variant: 'success' });
    onAfterUpdate?.();
  },
  onError: () => toast({ description: deleteFailMessage, variant: 'destructive' }),
});

const [commitResendMutation, { loading: resendLoading }] = useMutation(resendMutation, {
  onCompleted: () => toast({ description: resendSuccessMessage, variant: 'success' }),
  onError: () => toast({ description: resendFailMessage, variant: 'destructive' }),
});
```

Define all i18n messages at the top of the component:

```tsx
const updateSuccessMessage = intl.formatMessage({
  id: 'Feature / Update / Success',
  defaultMessage: 'Updated successfully!',
});

const resendSuccessMessage = intl.formatMessage({
  id: 'Feature / Resend / Success',
  defaultMessage: 'Resent successfully!',
});
```

## Common TypeScript Pitfalls to Avoid

### 1. String Storage vs Union Types

When storing values like `sortBy` as a generic `string` (e.g., in localStorage/sessionStorage or generic hooks), but the consuming component expects a specific union type, **cast when passing to the component**:

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG - Will cause type error
<FilterBar sortBy={filters.sortBy} />

// ✅ CORRECT - Cast to the expected union type
<FilterBar sortBy={filters.sortBy as ProjectSortOption} />
```

### 2. useState Callback vs Direct Value Setters

When replacing `useState` setters with custom hook setters, be aware that custom setters may only accept **direct values**, not callbacks:

```tsx
// useState supports callback syntax:
const [items, setItems] = useState<string[]>([]);
setItems((prev) => prev.filter((i) => i !== id)); // ✅ Works

// Custom hooks may only support direct values:
const { filters, setFilter } = useListFilters();
setFilter('items', (prev) => prev.filter(...)); // ❌ May not work

// Use the current value directly instead:
setFilter('items', filters.items.filter((i) => i !== id)); // ✅ Works
```

When updating `activeFilters` callbacks that remove items:

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG - Callback won't work with direct-value setters
(status) => setSelectedStatuses((prev) => prev.filter((s) => s !== status))

// ✅ CORRECT - Use current value and add explicit type
(status: string) => setSelectedStatuses(selectedStatuses.filter((s) => s !== status))
```

### 3. ESLint Disable Comments

**Never use `eslint-disable-next-line react-hooks/exhaustive-deps`** - this rule is not configured in the project and will cause lint errors. Instead:

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG - Rule doesn't exist, causes lint error
useEffect(() => {
  doSomething();
  // eslint-disable-next-line react-hooks/exhaustive-deps
}, [partialDeps]);

// ✅ CORRECT - Add all dependencies properly
useEffect(() => {
  doSomething();
}, [partialDeps, initializeState, otherDep]);
```

### 4. Callback Type Annotations in useMemo

When creating callbacks inside `useMemo` that will be passed to child components, add explicit parameter types:

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG - Implicit 'any' type errors
const callbacks = useMemo(() => [
  (item) => removeItem(items.filter((i) => i !== item)),
], [items]);

// ✅ CORRECT - Explicit type annotation
const callbacks = useMemo(() => [
  (item: string) => removeItem(items.filter((i) => i !== item)),
], [items, removeItem]);
```

## Preventing Infinite Loops in Custom Hooks

### 1. Array/Object Props Create New References

When passing arrays or objects as hook options, they get recreated on every render, causing infinite loops if used in dependency arrays:

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG - Creates new array on every render, causes infinite loop
export const useMyHook = () => {
  return useBaseHook({
    excludeKeys: ['a', 'b'], // New array every render!
    defaultValues: { x: 1 }, // New object every render!
  });
};

// ✅ CORRECT - Define stable constants outside the hook
const EXCLUDE_KEYS = ['a', 'b'];
const DEFAULT_VALUES = { x: 1 };

export const useMyHook = () => {
  return useBaseHook({
    excludeKeys: EXCLUDE_KEYS,
    defaultValues: DEFAULT_VALUES,
  });
};
```

### 2. Use Refs for Config Props in Custom Hooks

When building custom hooks that accept configuration props, use refs to prevent re-renders:

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG - Using config props in dependencies causes loops
export const useListFilters = ({ defaultFilters, excludeKeys }) => {
  const persistToStorage = useCallback((filters) => {
    for (const key of excludeKeys) { /* ... */ }
  }, [excludeKeys]); // excludeKeys changes every render!
};

// ✅ CORRECT - Store config in refs
export const useListFilters = ({ defaultFilters, excludeKeys }) => {
  const defaultFiltersRef = useRef(defaultFilters);
  const excludeKeysRef = useRef(excludeKeys);
  
  // Update refs without triggering re-renders
  defaultFiltersRef.current = defaultFilters;
  excludeKeysRef.current = excludeKeys;

  const persistToStorage = useCallback((filters) => {
    for (const key of excludeKeysRef.current) { /* ... */ }
  }, []); // No dependencies needed!
};
```

### 3. Avoid useEffect for Prop-Derived State

Using `useEffect` to sync state with prop changes can cause cascading updates. Use synchronous render-time checks instead:

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG - useEffect causes extra render cycle and potential loops
const [filters, setFilters] = useState(defaultFilters);

useEffect(() => {
  if (tenantId !== prevTenantId) {
    setFilters(loadFromStorage(tenantId));
  }
}, [tenantId, prevTenantId]);

// ✅ CORRECT - Synchronous check during render
const initializedTenantRef = useRef<string | undefined>(undefined);
const [filters, setFilters] = useState(() => {
  initializedTenantRef.current = tenantId;
  return loadFromStorage(tenantId);
});

// Check during render (before return)
if (tenantId !== initializedTenantRef.current) {
  initializedTenantRef.current = tenantId;
  setFilters(loadFromStorage(tenantId));
}
```

### 4. useSearchParams Can Cause Instability

`useSearchParams` from react-router returns a new object on every URL change. Avoid using it in dependency arrays:

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG - searchParams changes frequently
const [searchParams] = useSearchParams();

const initState = useCallback(() => {
  return parseFromUrl(searchParams);
}, [searchParams]); // Triggers on every URL change!

useEffect(() => {
  setState(initState());
}, [initState]); // Infinite loop risk!

// ✅ CORRECT - Read searchParams directly without dependencies
const [searchParams] = useSearchParams();

const [state] = useState(() => {
  // Read once during initialization
  return parseFromUrl(searchParams);
});
```

### 5. Callback Dependencies with useCallback

When a `useCallback` depends on frequently-changing values, and that callback is used in a `useEffect`, infinite loops can occur:

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG - initializeState changes when searchParams changes
const initializeState = useCallback(() => {
  return readFromUrl(searchParams);
}, [searchParams]);

useEffect(() => {
  setState(initializeState());
}, [initializeState]); // Runs every time searchParams changes!

// ✅ CORRECT - Don't include callback in useEffect deps
useEffect(() => {
  setState(initializeState());
}, [tenantId]); // Only run when tenantId actually changes
```
